<TITLE> BIMSTEC members agree to create food bank </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 09 (bdnews24.com)Seven countries of South Asia and Southeast Asia Wednesday agreed in principle to set up a food bank for them to confront the soaring prices of food and the fallout from climate change. But the establishment of the proposed food bank would be placed at the next ministerial meeting scheduled for the second half of next year after scrutiny, according to a decision taken at the first ministerial meeting of BIMSTEC on poverty alleviation. The ministers or minister-level officials from Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Myanmar, Nepal, Sri Lanka and Thailand met in the city and recommended seven issues for alleviation of poverty in the regional grouping BIMSTEC, established in 1997. "We recommended setting-up a food bank for BIMSTEC countries and will scrutinise its establishment," finance adviser AB Mirza Azizul Islam told reporters after the end of the two-day meeting. The adviser briefed the reporters on the outcome of the conference on poverty alleviation. The senior officials of the member countries drafted a set of recommendations Tuesday for the ministerial meeting. The ministerial conference adopted a charter of seven antipoverty recommendations. "The proposal (food bank) will be placed at the next ministerial meeting which will be held in the second quarter of next year in Nepal," the adviser said. He said BIMSTEC members had agreed to work out a work plan for alleviation of poverty in the member countries. "The main outcome of the conference is that we have agreed to foster mutual collaboration on alleviation of poverty among the member countries," Azizul Islam said. The meeting also recommended enhancing mutual cooperation on climate change and sustainable development. Bhutan's finance minister Lyonpo Wangdi Norbu, India's state minister for rural development Chandra Sekhar Sahu, Myanmar's deputy minister for national planning and economic development Col Thuyain Zaw, Nepal's national planning commission member Dr Posh Raj Pandey, Sri Lanka's minister for nation building and state infrastructure development RMK Ratnayake and Thailand's social development and human security minister Chavarat Charnvirakul were among those attending the ministerial conference. The ministerial conference on poverty alleviation took place as per a decision of the first summit of the Bay of Bengal Multi-Sectoral Technical and Economic Cooperation in 2004 in Bangkok. Chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed inaugurated the conference Wednesday at Hotel Sorangaon. bdn
